faq:
  - q: "How do I calculate how many pavers I need?"
    a: "Calculate the patio area, calculate the area of one paver, then divide patio area by paver area. This calculator also adds overage for cuts, breakage, and layout waste."
  - q: "How much overage should I add for pavers?"
    a: "A 10% overage is common for basic layouts. Complex patterns, diagonal layouts, borders, curves, and lots of cuts may require more."
  - q: "How much base gravel do I need for pavers?"
    a: "Base gravel is calculated from patio area multiplied by base depth. Many pedestrian patios use several inches of compacted base, but local soil and project requirements matter."
  - q: "How much sand goes under pavers?"
    a: "Many paver projects use about 1 inch of leveling sand over a compacted base. Always follow the paver manufacturer's installation guidance."
  - q: "Can this calculator be used for irregular patios?"
    a: "It is best for rectangular or square patios. For curved or irregular shapes, estimate the area separately and add extra overage for cuts and waste."
  - q: "Do pavers need a gravel base?"
    a: "Most paver patios and walkways need a compacted base to reduce settling and movement. Base requirements depend on soil, climate, drainage, and use."
  - q: "Should I include joints between pavers?"
    a: "For rough material estimates, paver dimensions usually get you close. Joint spacing, pattern, and edging can affect the final count."
  - q: "How do I estimate pavers for a walkway?"
    a: "Use the walkway length and width as the project area, then enter your paver dimensions. Add overage if the walkway has curves or cuts."
  - q: "Are larger pavers easier to estimate?"
    a: "Larger pavers may require fewer pieces, but they can be heavier and may create more noticeable cuts at edges. Layout still matters."
  - q: "Should I buy all pavers at once?"
    a: "For color consistency, it is often smart to buy enough pavers from the same batch or order, especially for visible patio projects."
